---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { SITE } from '../config.js';

const description =
  'Why AEO Decoded pulled Season 3 two episodes in, rebuilt its own site from WordPress to the edge, and relaunched with a new editorial standard: principles or tested results — nothing else ships.';

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'The Reset: why Season 3 starts over',
  description,
  author: { '@type': 'Person', name: SITE.author },
  publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: SITE.studioName, url: SITE.studioUrl },
  mainEntityOfPage: new URL('/the-reset/', SITE.url).href,
};
---

<Base title="The Reset" description={description} schema={schema} currentPath="/the-reset/">
  <article class="prose">
    <header class="episode-head">
      <p class="field field--blue">Announcement // Season 3</p>
      <h1>The Reset</h1>
      <p class="citable">
        <mark>We pulled the first two episodes of Season 3, rebuilt this site from
        WordPress to the edge, and set a new bar: nothing ships unless it's a
        principle or a tested result.</mark>
      </p>
    </header>

    <h2>What happened</h2>
    <p>
      Two episodes into recording Season 3, I stopped. The episodes were about
      building AEO into a new site — and the advice in them was true. I'd seen it
      work. But I kept hitting the same honest problem: <em>it all depends on how
      you're set up.</em> Advice that's conditional on your architecture isn't a
      method. It's a maybe.
    </p>
    <p>
      Seasons 1 and 2 covered the fundamentals of Answer Engine Optimization in
      depth, and I stand behind them. But the field around us was filling up with
      tactics — the kind that expire the way SEO tricks always have. I didn't want
      to add to that pile. I didn't want to publish anything I couldn't get behind
      as a genuinely improved approach.
    </p>

    <h2>What changed</h2>
    <p>
      So instead of recording, I built. This site — the one you're reading — was
      moved off WordPress and deployed as a custom static architecture on a global
      edge network. No plugins, no database, no bloat between the content and the
      machines reading it. The same standard I built for
      <a href={SITE.studioUrl} rel="noopener">the studio</a>: perfect Lighthouse
      scores, machine-readable structure, and every AEO principle from the show
      running live on every page.
    </p>
    <p>
      That's the difference between talking about the method and being the method.
      This site is now the test bench for everything the podcast claims.
    </p>

    <h2>The new standard</h2>
    <p>
      Season 3 runs on one editorial rule: every episode is either a
      <strong>principle</strong> — something true about how machines read the web
      that doesn't expire with the next model release — or a
      <strong>tested result</strong> — something we tried on a real site, measured,
      and can show you. Circulating tactics we can't verify don't ship. If the
      industry is pushing something we haven't proven, we'll test it first and
      report what actually happened.
    </p>

    <h2>What's coming</h2>
    <p>
      Season 3 is a build log. The WordPress-to-edge migration you're standing on.
      The schema layer. The measurement system. And the part nobody in this field
      shows you: tracking whether any of it actually earns citations from ChatGPT,
      Perplexity, and Gemini — in public, with receipts.
    </p>
    <p>
      Seasons 1 and 2 are all here in the <a href="/episodes/">archive</a> if you
      want the fundamentals first. Season 3 is where we prove them.
    </p>
    <p>— {SITE.author}</p>

    <section class="cta-strip">
      <p class="field">Follow along</p>
      <h2>Don't miss the relaunch.</h2>
      <p>
        Follow the show on your favorite platform and you'll get Season 3 the moment
        it lands.
      </p>
      <a class="button" href="/#listen">Choose your platform</a>
    </section>
  </article>
</Base>
